The higher price points of cohort-based courses mean categorically different expectations. Books, articles, blog posts, and tweets all focus on the what and why. Great courses have to focus on the how. https://t.co/kQ2SLYt4Hd
@wes_kao IMO, there are programs that focus only on the HOW, and this causes a different sort of problem. Some tasks require you to make judgement calls and trade-offs in a given context...if you don't really understand the WHY, you could end up doing it all wrong.
@Pvaliathan @wes_kao This.

I recently heard from a creative director that they discarded all the UX
designers who had learned at General Assembly. (I was surprised to hear this.)

The reason?

The graduates only new the how. And just one formulaic approach to that how. They couldn‚Äôt do why or what.
@fehler @Pvaliathan The how isn‚Äôt only about tools and how to execute. 

This might partially be a semantics issue. For design, the how could include how to evaluate a situation with nuance, how to develop your sense of taste, how to identify the root cause of issues. Those are all useful how‚Äôs.
@fehler @Pvaliathan To me, how doesn‚Äôt mean having a hammer and thinking everything is a nail, ie having a formulaic one-dimensional approach. It includes learning how to use the ‚Äúwhat‚Äù with critical thinking, depth, and good judgement.

Training your team to think rigorously means spending time upfront.

You either (a) spend time on training or (b) spend time fixing mistakes. 

You spend time either way. Except one is an investment &amp; the other is a never-ending slog
@wes_kao Do you have any examples of how you all go about doing this? Is it culture, inter-personal, or more tactical like certain SOPs or structures?
@lcrothlisberger @wes_kao +1 for some examples of training best practices, please @wes_kao
@rdstevenson @lcrothlisberger @wes_kao Not Wes, but two things I've seen help:

1. Onboarding that requires self-directed critical thought. As much guidance as advanced math textbooks.

2. Culture of long-term thinking. This has to come from the top, but this is very teachable if the environment doesn't suffocate it.
@MattMHarriman @rdstevenson @wes_kao Thanks for your input. Both are great points, #2 about a culture of long-term thinking really got me. Man, that is so true, but I have never thought of labeling it as such.
@lcrothlisberger @rdstevenson @wes_kao Thanks.

I was in an org where the only quarter that mattered was this one, and that made every quarter harder than the last...

